<TITLE> 256 organisations linked to militancy: Barkat </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 17 (bdnews24.com) -- Abul Barkat, a leading economist, on Monday claimed that 256 private organisations, financed by some quarters, are linked to fundamentalism and militancy. He said the fundamentalist forces have invested money in nine important sectors, including banks, insurance, education, mass media, health and information technology. Addressing an Awami League rally at city's Bangabandhu Avenue, Barkat, chairman of the state-owned Janata Bank, said he believed that the government knows who are financing these militant organisations. "I don't believe that the government doesn't know where the organisations are getting the finance from." Awami League organised the rally to mark party chief Sheikh Hasina's homecoming anniversary. "There are 125 militant organisations, small and large, including one arm of Jamaat-e-Islami, which was exposed during the BDR mutiny", he said. He expressed his concern that trial of war crimes would be hindered unless militants are controlled. Awami League acting president Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury urged the countrymen to be alert against any move harmful to the country. "Many things are happening in the country. Keep vigil to ensure none can harm the country." Party joint secretary Mahbub-ul-Alam Hanif alleged that opposition BNP is hatching conspiracy against democracy "when the government is carrying out different development works." He urged BNP not to misguide the people through "staging drama". Home minister Sahara Khatun, Awami League organising secretary and state minister for local government Jahangir Kabir Nanak, party presidium member Yusuf Hossain Humayun, and law affairs secretary Abdul Matin Khasru, among others, addressed the rall
